thread_root_message.markdown_content: yeah i think Sequences (or whatever we call what we show in the Inbox) should also not pull from different channels, it creates a lot of edge cases as it relates to permissioning and read/unread states. the same Stack topic (ex. Artifact) could have different Events depending on what channels/convos a user has access to. this could end up giving people at the company different understandings of the same topic. marking a Stack "read" in Inbox marks all the component Events read too, but as they're not delivering chronologically, this would lead to confusing read/unread states when a user views messages in a channel vs. in the Inbox.

thread_root_message.markdown_content: yeah i think Sequences (or whatever we call what we show in the Inbox) should also not pull from different channels, it creates a lot of edge cases as it relates to permissioning and read/unread states. the same Stack topic (ex. Artifact) could have different Events depending on what channels/convos a user has access to. this could end up giving people at the company different understandings of the same topic. marking a Stack "read" in Inbox marks all the component Events read too, but as they're not delivering chronologically, this would lead to confusing read/unread states when a user views messages in a channel vs. in the Inbox.

conversation.summary_text: Oli and Peter are collaborating on Ando‚Äôs inbox design and related development (GitHub PRs, Notion bugs, Figma explorations, Linear docs, including use cases/sample data). They clarified that the inbox‚Äôs core job is to show ‚Äúwhat‚Äôs new‚Äù (badges, newest at top), with no grouping as the default. Optional grouping modes should make information more digestible without semantic grouping, and must clearly explain why items are grouped. Acceptable groupings include bursty multi-part messages and multiple reactions to a message, with a toggleable ‚Äústack‚Äù view for summarized groups.

message.markdown_content: The point of InboxBe the source of what‚Äôs new in their workspaceShow badgesPut new crap at the topPresent that information to them digestiblyGroup new eventsSummarizeThe $1M QuestionHow do we summarize information with as little loss as possible?Approach 2Group by 1) similar topic + 2) time close togetherApproach 1Group by 1) same conversation, 2) same author, 3) time close togetherApproach 4Group thread replies, DMs, and reactions, regardless of timeTLDR;Default is no grouping! Just make sure we accomplish #1They can then view as stack. This accomplishes #2. It is a toggle as to not cannibalize #1.We will offer ways to change how events are grouped in case we get it wrong.This is why we shouldn‚Äôt have semantic groupsBecause we don‚Äôt know how each user wants to group incoming events, we could get it wrong -> information is less digestible!We will offer ways to change how events are groupedWe need to show why it was grouped this wayThey can just turn it offWhat you would expect to see in a groupMessage that could have been one message, but was instead sent in burst -> should be a groupMultiple people reacted to your message -> should be a group

conversation.summary_text: Oli and Peter are collaborating on Ando‚Äôs inbox design and related development (GitHub PRs, Notion bugs, Figma explorations, Linear docs, including use cases/sample data). They clarified that the inbox‚Äôs core job is to show ‚Äúwhat‚Äôs new‚Äù (badges, newest at top), with no grouping as the default. Optional grouping modes should make information more digestible without semantic grouping, and must clearly explain why items are grouped. Acceptable groupings include bursty multi-part messages and multiple reactions to a message, with a toggleable ‚Äústack‚Äù view for summarized groups.

yeah i think this is helpful!

person a: ‚Äùhow is ando different to slack, why should i use it?‚Äù
person b: ‚Äùando is faster. how? it activates your workspace chatter context. so you can do things like search semantically. you can ask ando about topics in your workspace that you‚Äôd have to hunt through messages, recall what mattered, and manually package etc. etc.‚Äù

"faster" for now is not the most specific/telling/convincing, but it‚Äôs starting to get there and will hone in our focus in the meantime - i want to be able to express "why ando" w/ a structure like the above, where it's something like:

ando is {adj} -> ando does {verb}s -> ando's {feature} allows you to {something cool/new/useful} whereas in other comms/productivity tools you'd have to {something not cool/new/useful}

message.markdown_content:
i worry a bit about taking user wording at face value (per saddles memo). People are good at describing pain, not solutions. So when we hear ‚ÄúSlack isn‚Äôt slow,‚Äù I don‚Äôt take that as definitive - it might just mean ‚Äúslow‚Äù isn‚Äôt the frame they‚Äôd use, even if there‚Äôs still a real efficiency or attention problem underneath. 

I‚Äôm not claiming speed is the right framing, just that we shouldn‚Äôt anchor too hard on the words.
